    <article class="prose">
      <p>
        I'm Jayden — a <strong>Computer Science and Linguistics double major at UCLA</strong>.
        The pairing is deliberate: linguistics is the study of language as a formal
        system, and I want to build software that actually works with that system —
        which today means AI.
      </p>
      <p>
        Right now I'm interning at <strong>MDBL</strong>, a dental practice brokerage,
        where I build AI automation for the deal pipeline: restructuring their Notion
        CRM, wiring up Make.com scenarios, and turning manual back-office work into
        systems that run on their own. It's taught me that the hard part of automation
        is rarely the code — it's understanding how the business actually uses its data.
      </p>
      <p>
        On the side I build trading systems for prediction markets. My current project
        is an <a href="/projects/kalshi-trading-bot/">async Python bot for Kalshi</a> that
        streams live market data over WebSocket and manages simulated positions against
        their sandbox — an excuse to go deep on asyncio, failure handling, and state
        that has to survive restarts.
      </p>
      <p>
        Before UCLA, I founded <strong>Kode for Kids</strong>, a free coding program for
        middle schoolers in my hometown of Monterey Park — 100+ students learned Python
        and Java fundamentals through it. Teaching something is still the fastest way I
        know to find the gaps in my own understanding.
      </p>
      <p>
        Off the clock: syntax trees, prediction markets, and finding the best noodles
        in the San Gabriel Valley.
      </p>
      <p>
        The fastest way to reach me is
        <a href="mailto:jaydentphu@gmail.com">email</a> — I read everything.
      </p>
    </article>
